{"type":"message","id":"55dea1a1","parentId":"ebb8fb83","timestamp":"2026-03-19T01:16:09.492Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_jzjpfwj6h28l_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: Artificial Intelligence\n\nURL Source: http://www.theverge.com/ai\n\nMarkdown Content:\n![Image 1: Jay Peters](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/01/JAY_BLURPLE.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nJay Peters Two hours ago\n\nPerplexity has released its Comet browser on iOS.\n\n![Image 2: Charles Pulliam-Moore](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/author_profile_images/195801/CHARLES_PULLIAM-MOORE.0.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nCharles Pulliam-Moore Mar 18\n\nAn AI-generated Val Kilmer will star in a new movie.\n\nThough Val Kilmer — who [died last December](https://www.nytimes.com/2025/04/01/movies/val-kilmer-dead.html) — was too sick to actually shoot any scenes after being cast in writer / director Coerte Voorhees’ upcoming film _As Deep As The Grave_, [_Variety_ reports](https://variety.com/2026/film/news/val-kilmer-ai-film-as-deep-as-the-grave-1236691042/) that Kilmer’s estate has agreed to let an AI-generated facsimile of the actor appear in the movie.\n\n![Image 3: Jay Peters](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/01/JAY_BLURPLE.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nJay Peters Mar 18\n\nGoogle is trying to make “vibe design” happen.\n\nIn a post announcing [some updates coming](https://blog.google/innovation-and-ai/models-and-research/google-labs/stitch-ai-ui-design/) to Stitch, Google’s [AI coding tool for UI design](https://www.theverge.com/news/670773/google-labs-stitch-ui-coding-design-tool), the company is encouraging users to “vibe design,” including with new voice capabilities. I’m so tired of vibing.\n\n![Image 4: Hayden Field](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/06/HAYDEN_BLURPLE.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nHayden Field Mar 18\n\nThe Pentagon filed a rebuttal to Anthropic’s lawsuit.\n\nAnthropic filed a lawsuit earlier this month over its “supply chain risk” designation, but the Department of Defense held firm in a new [court filing](https://www.courtlistener.com/docket/72379655/96/anthropic-pbc-v-us-department-of-war/), alleging that the company could ostensibly “attempt to disable its technology or preemptively alter the behavior of its model either before or during ongoing warfighting operations” in the event it felt its red lines were “being crossed.” The filing added that the Pentagon “deemed that an unacceptable risk to national security.”\n\n![Image 5: Stevie Bonifield](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/STEVIE_BONIFIELD_BLURPLE.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nStevie Bonifield Mar 18\n\nMeta’s NYC store is here to stay.\n\nThe Tardis-blue Meta Lab NYC store on Fifth Avenue in Manhattan is no longer a pop-up shop. Meta [announced on Wednesday](https://www.meta.com/blog/meta-lab-new-locations-new-york-city-fifth-avenue-wynn-las-vegas-west-hollywood-new-york-ai-glasses-demos/) that the skateboarding-themed glasses store is now a “permanent flagship location,” where it will continue selling its [AI smart glasses](https://www.theverge.com/tech/779566/meta-ray-ban-display-hands-on-smart-glasses-price-battery-specs) and Meta Quest headsets.\n\n[![Image 6: The interior of Meta’s NYC flagship store](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/meta-lab-nyc-interior.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&w=2400)](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/meta-lab-nyc-interior.jpg?quality=90&strip=all)\n\n[![Image 7: The exterior of Meta’s NYC flagship store](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/meta-lab-nyc-storefront.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&w=2400)](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/meta-lab-nyc-storefront.jpg?quality=90&strip=all)\n\n**1/2**Image: Meta\n\n![Image 8: DLSS 5: Has Nvidia’s AI graphics technology gone too far?](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/screencapture-nvidia-en-us-geforce-news-dlss5-breakthrough-in-visual-fidelity-for-games-nvidia-dlss-5-resident-evil-requiem-geforce-rtx-comparison-screenshot-001-2026-03-17-20_21_56.png?quality=90&strip=all&crop=21.875%2C0%2C56.25%2C100&w=2400)![Image 9: DLSS 5: Has Nvidia’s AI graphics technology gone too far?](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/screencapture-nvidia-en-us-geforce-news-dlss5-breakthrough-in-visual-fidelity-for-games-nvidia-dlss-5-resident-evil-requiem-geforce-rtx-comparison-screenshot-001-2026-03-17-20_21_56.png?quality=90&strip=all&crop=7.8125%2C0%2C84.375%2C100&w=2400)\n\nRichard Lawler Mar 18\n\n![Image 10: Jess Weatherbed](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/author_profile_images/195820/JESSICA_WEATHERBED.0.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nJess Weatherbed Mar 18\n\nSony working to fight Ghibli-infringing slop.\n\nAlongside building tools to identify [AI song sources](https://www.theverge.com/ai-artificial-intelligence/879865/sony-develops-tech-to-identify-source-material-for-ai-songs), Sony’s R&D division is reportedly training its own “Protective AI” model on content from Studio Ghibli films, which are [popular fodder](https://www.theverge.com/openai/636529/images-chatgpt-openai-studio-ghibli-copyright) for [generated imitation](https://www.theverge.com/tech/638603/studio-ghibli-chatgpt-ai-filter-white-house-meme). Sony hasn’t decided what it’ll do with the model (yet), but it’s designed to eventually stop AI from ripping off _any_ protected content.\n\n![Image 11: Jess Weatherbed](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/author_profile_images/195820/JESSICA_WEATHERBED.0.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nJess Weatherbed Mar 18\n\nWhich anti-AI banner should human creators rally around?\n\n_[BBC News](https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/articles/cj0d6el50ppo)_ has counted eight different initiatives trying to establish a label that distinguishes human-made products and services from those using AI. Experts say a single standard must be chosen to avoid confusing consumers, but getting everyone to agree on what counts as “human-made” is hard because AI is already integrated into so many tools.\n\n[![Image 12: Labels and stamps have been launched by companies and non-profits from the UK, Australia and the US.](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/72c339a0-1eca-11f1-9120-a910fc22c6ac.png.webp?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=2400)](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/72c339a0-1eca-11f1-9120-a910fc22c6ac.png.webp?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0,0,100,100)\n\n![Image 13: Jay Peters](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/01/JAY_BLURPLE.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nJay Peters Mar 17\n\nJensen Huang, on the critical reaction to DLSS 5: “Well, first of all, they’re completely wrong.”\n\n“The reason for that is because, as I have explained very carefully, DLSS 5 fuses controllability of the of geometry and textures and everything about the game with generative AI,” Huang said, [according to _Tom’s Hardware_](https://www.tomshardware.com/pc-components/gpus/jensen-huang-says-gamers-are-completely-wrong-about-dlss-5-nvidia-ceo-responds-to-dlss-5-backlash), and he noted that developers can “fine-tune the generative AI.”\n\n![Image 14: Richard Lawler](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/01/RICHARD_BLURPLE.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nRichard Lawler Mar 17\n\nCiting fake cases in your court filing can be costly.\n\nThey claimed that the court order was “void on its face.” Now [they’re on the hook for $15k each](https://storage.courtlistener.com/recap/gov.uscourts.ca6.152857/gov.uscourts.ca6.152857.50.2.pdf) to start, plus a long list of costs and fees that will certainly add up.\n\n![Image 15: Nvidia’s DLSS 5 is like motion smoothing for video games, but worse](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/Screenshot-2026-03-17-at-1.29.30%E2%80%AFPM.png?quality=90&strip=all&crop=21.825063078217%2C0%2C56.349873843566%2C100&w=2400)![Image 16: Nvidia’s DLSS 5 is like motion smoothing for video games, but worse](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/Screenshot-2026-03-17-at-1.29.30%E2%80%AFPM.png?quality=90&strip=all&crop=7.7375946173255%2C0%2C84.524810765349%2C100&w=2400)\n\n![Image 17: Now everyone in the US is getting Google’s personalized Gemini AI](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/01/google-gemini-ai-personal-intelligence-tire-suggestion-demo.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=22.093023255814%2C0%2C55.813953488372%2C100&w=2400)![Image 18: Now everyone in the US is getting Google’s personalized Gemini AI](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/01/google-gemini-ai-personal-intelligence-tire-suggestion-demo.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=8.1395348837209%2C0%2C83.720930232558%2C100&w=2400)\n\n![Image 19: Microsoft appoints a new Copilot boss after AI leadership shake-up](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/07/STK259_MICROSOFT_COPILOT_2__C.png?quality=90&strip=all&crop=16.666666666667%2C0%2C66.666666666667%2C100&w=2400)![Image 20: Microsoft appoints a new Copilot boss after AI leadership shake-up](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/07/STK259_MICROSOFT_COPILOT_2__C.png?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=2400)\n\n![Image 21: The future of code is exciting and terrifying](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/VRG_VST_0317_Site.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=16.666666666667%2C0%2C66.666666666667%2C100&w=2400)![Image 22: The future of code is exciting and terrifying](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/VRG_VST_0317_Site.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=2400)\n\n![Image 23: Robert Hart](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/09/ROB_H_BLURPLE.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nRobert Hart Mar 17\n\nOpenAI cuts back on “side quests.”\n\nCEO of applications Fidji Simo told staff the company will prioritize coding and enterprise users over the wide array of projects it has been pursuing, the _WSJ_ reports, including [deepfake machine Sora](https://www.theverge.com/ai-artificial-intelligence/893189/openai-chatgpt-sora-integration), [browser Atlas](https://www.theverge.com/ai-artificial-intelligence/803475/openais-ai-powered-browser-chatgpt-atlas-google-chrome-competition-agent), and [gadgets](https://www.theverge.com/ai-artificial-intelligence/882077/openai-chatgpt-smart-speaker-camera-glasses-lamp).\n\n![Image 24: Sean Hollister](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/author_profile_images/196092/sean-nerf-profile-pic..0.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nSean Hollister Mar 16\n\nHere’s the moment Frozen’s Olaf joined the Nvidia GTC 2026 keynote.\n\nNvidia has uploaded the GTC 26 replay, and the embed above _should_ be queued up to the Olaf part. ([I met Olaf yesterday](https://www.theverge.com/tech/895369/olaf-disney-imagineering-frozen-robot-up-close)!) Right after that, you can help me witness what appears to be an entirely AI-generated music video that attempts to summarize the keynote. It is quite the thing.\n\n![Image 25: Stevie Bonifield](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/STEVIE_BONIFIELD_BLURPLE.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nStevie Bonifield Mar 16\n\nNvidia is launching NemoClaw, a more secure version of OpenClaw.\n\nDuring [GTC](https://www.theverge.com/ai-artificial-intelligence/895363/how-to-watch-nvidias-gtc-2026-keynote-tap-here) on Monday, Nvidia announced it’s [launching NemoClaw](https://nvidianews.nvidia.com/news/nvidia-announces-nemoclaw), an agentic AI platform that adds privacy and security protections to the autonomous AI platform [OpenClaw](https://www.theverge.com/news/872091/openclaw-moltbot-clawdbot-ai-agent-news) by running it in an “isolated sandbox” environment:\n\n> NemoClaw uses Nvidia Agent Toolkit software to optimize OpenClaw in a single command. It installs OpenShell to provide open models and an isolated sandbox that adds data privacy and security to autonomous agents. This provides the missing infrastructure layer beneath claws to give them the access they need to be productive, while enforcing policy-based security, network and privacy guardrails.\n\n![Image 26: Sean Hollister](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/author_profile_images/196092/sean-nerf-profile-pic..0.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nSean Hollister Mar 16\n\nNvidia is the latest to promise AI data centers in space.\n\n> We’re working with our partners on a new computer called Vera Ruben Space 1, and it’s going to go out to space and start data centers out in space. Now, of course in space there’s no conduction, there’s no convection, there’s just radiation, and so we have to figure out how to cool these systems out in space. But we’ve got lots of great engineers working on it.\n\n![Image 27: DLSS 5 looks like a real-time generative AI filter for video games](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/grokashcroft.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=16.650485436893%2C0%2C66.699029126214%2C100&w=2400)![Image 28: DLSS 5 looks like a real-time generative AI filter for video games](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/grokashcroft.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0.024260067928189%2C100%2C99.951479864144&w=2400)\n\n![Image 29: Teens sue Elon Musk’s xAI over Grok’s AI-generated CSAM](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/05/STK262_GROK_B_C.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=16.666666666667%2C0%2C66.666666666667%2C100&w=2400)![Image 30: Teens sue Elon Musk’s xAI over Grok’s AI-generated CSAM](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/05/STK262_GROK_B_C.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=2400)\n\n![Image 31: Benjamin Netanyahu is struggling to prove he’s not an AI clone](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/Benjamin-Netanyahu-alleged-ai-deepfake-hed.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=16.666666666667%2C0%2C66.666666666667%2C100&w=2400)![Image 32: Benjamin Netanyahu is struggling to prove he’s not an AI clone](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/Benjamin-Netanyahu-alleged-ai-deepfake-hed.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=2400)\n\n![Image 33: Encyclopedia Britannica is suing OpenAI for allegedly ‘memorizing’ its content with ChatGPT](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/gettyimages-141320386.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=16.65%2C0%2C66.7%2C100&w=2400)![Image 34: Encyclopedia Britannica is suing OpenAI for allegedly ‘memorizing’ its content with ChatGPT](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/gettyimages-141320386.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0.02498750624688%2C100%2C99.950024987506&w=2400)\n\n![Image 35: Sean Hollister](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/author_profile_images/196092/sean-nerf-profile-pic..0.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nSean Hollister Mar 16\n\nHow to watch Nvidia’s GTC 2026 keynote: tap here.\n\nThe world’s [first $5 trillion company](https://www.theverge.com/news/809017/nvidia-5-trillion-market-cap-ai) (currently 4.47 trillion) is strutting its stuff in San Jose, California. We’re expecting an AI and robot show... but fingers crossed [for N1 consumer laptop chips](https://www.theverge.com/games/867056/leak-nvidia-n1-n1x-laptops-lenovo-dell) too! Jensen’s keynote starts 11am PT / 2pm ET.\n\n![Image 36: Yahoo CEO Jim Lanzone on reviving the web’s homepage](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/DCD-20260316-Lanzone.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=2400)\n\nHow Yahoo escaped its Verizon death spiral and became profitable again.\n\n![Image 37: Emma Roth](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/author_profile_images/195810/EMMA_ROTH.0.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nEmma Roth Mar 16\n\nMoltbook updates its rules about what you and your AI can do.\n\nJust days after Meta acquired the “social” network for AI agents, the platform has [updated its terms of service](https://www.moltbook.com/terms), stating that users must be 13 years of age or older to use the site and are “solely responsible” for actions taken by their AI agents, whether they “act autonomously or otherwise, and irrespective of whether such actions or omissions were intended.”\n\n![Image 38: This is not a fly uploaded to a computer](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/Screenshot-2026-03-13-at-17.18.37.png?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0.67971723762915%2C100%2C98.640565524742&w=2400)\n\nA lot of buzz, but not much evidence.\n\n![Image 39: OpenAI’s adult mode will reportedly be smutty, not pornographic](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25313355/STK464_PORN_ADULT_CONTENT_2A.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=17.303921568627%2C0%2C65.392156862745%2C100&w=2400)![Image 40: OpenAI’s adult mode will reportedly be smutty, not pornographic](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25313355/STK464_PORN_ADULT_CONTENT_2A.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0.95588235294118%2C0%2C98.088235294118%2C100&w=2400)\n\n![Image 41: Thomas Ricker](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/author_profile_images/196111/IMG_5981_2.0.jpeg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nThomas Ricker Mar 16\n\n“AI can be very dangerous, we have to be very careful with it,” says Trump.\n\n![Image 42: AI companies want to harvest improv actors’ skills to train AI on human emotion](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/268402_AI_companies_want_to_harvest_improv_actors_skills_to_train_large_AI_models_on_human_emotion_and_tone_CVirginia.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=2400)\n\nThe job requires the ‘ability to recognize, express, and shift between emotions in a way that feels authentic and human.’\n\n![Image 43: Terrence O'Brien](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/02/Terrence-OBrien-headshot-1.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nTerrence O'Brien Mar 14\n\nPalantir’s Maven Smart System is an AI-powered Kanban board for killing people.\n\nThe company recently hosted a series of speakers at [AIPCon](https://www.palantir.com/aipcon/), including Cameron Stanley, the Department of War’s Chief Digital and Artificial Intelligence Officer, who gave a [chilling demo](https://www.threads.com/@bilawal.ai/post/DV1Ev2miINv?xmt=AQF0ZXsOrxjnVEg_QRI1G9MROQaA9NpfBGwJTngl8DSYGsedlthnfzmOCT56rzDgkNtOYNqc&slof=1) of [Palantir’s](https://www.theverge.com/business/872928/palantirs-government-growth)[Maven Smart System](https://blog.palantir.com/maven-smart-system-innovating-for-the-alliance-5ebc31709eea), where anyone or anything can be targeted for a [military strike](https://www.theverge.com/ai-artificial-intelligence/885963/anthropic-dod-pentagon-tech-workers-ai-labs-react) with a “Left click, right click, left click.”\n\n![Image 44: Terrence O'Brien](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/02/Terrence-OBrien-headshot-1.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nTerrence O'Brien Mar 14\n\nAI has nearly killed Buzzfeed, but its CEO has learned nothing.\n\nThree years ago _Buzzfeed_ embraced AI, using it to generate articles and quiz responses. Turns out, nobody wants that. The company posted a [loss of $57.3 million](https://futurism.com/artificial-intelligence/buzzfeed-disastrous-earnings-ai) in 2025 and its stock dropped to just $0.70. But CEO Jonah Peretti is still planning to bring “[new AI apps](https://investors.buzzfeed.com/news-releases/news-release-details/buzzfeed-inc-reports-q4-and-full-year-2025-results)” to market. 🤦\n\n![Image 45: Microsoft’s Copilot AI assistant is coming to current-gen Xbox consoles this year](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25676324/twarren_xboxseriesxwhite__6_.JPG?quality=90&strip=all&crop=16.890243902439%2C0%2C66.219512195122%2C100&w=2400)![Image 46: Microsoft’s Copilot AI assistant is coming to current-gen Xbox consoles this year](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25676324/twarren_xboxseriesxwhite__6_.JPG?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0.33536585365853%2C0%2C99.329268292683%2C100&w=2400)\n\n![Image 47: Dominic Preston](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/01/DOM_BLURPLE-1.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nDominic Preston Mar 13\n\nAlexa, watch your language.\n\nAmazon has expanded its [Alexa Plus personality styles](https://www.theverge.com/tech/884269/amazon-alexa-plus-personality-styles-availability) with a new [“Sassy” option](https://www.theverge.com/tech/894135/amazons-sassy-personality-style-for-alexa-plus-has-a-lot-of-warning-labels#comments). The chili pepper icon hints at this Alexa’s “unfiltered personality,” but don’t worry, Amazon is keeping the spice mild, with only “occasional censored profanity.”\n\n**Chris K.:**"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":972,"aggregated":"Title: Artificial Intelligence\n\nURL Source: http://www.theverge.com/ai\n\nMarkdown Content:\n![Image 1: Jay Peters](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/01/JAY_BLURPLE.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nJay Peters Two hours ago\n\nPerplexity has released its Comet browser on iOS.\n\n![Image 2: Charles Pulliam-Moore](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/author_profile_images/195801/CHARLES_PULLIAM-MOORE.0.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nCharles Pulliam-Moore Mar 18\n\nAn AI-generated Val Kilmer will star in a new movie.\n\nThough Val Kilmer — who [died last December](https://www.nytimes.com/2025/04/01/movies/val-kilmer-dead.html) — was too sick to actually shoot any scenes after being cast in writer / director Coerte Voorhees’ upcoming film _As Deep As The Grave_, [_Variety_ reports](https://variety.com/2026/film/news/val-kilmer-ai-film-as-deep-as-the-grave-1236691042/) that Kilmer’s estate has agreed to let an AI-generated facsimile of the actor appear in the movie.\n\n![Image 3: Jay Peters](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/01/JAY_BLURPLE.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nJay Peters Mar 18\n\nGoogle is trying to make “vibe design” happen.\n\nIn a post announcing [some updates coming](https://blog.google/innovation-and-ai/models-and-research/google-labs/stitch-ai-ui-design/) to Stitch, Google’s [AI coding tool for UI design](https://www.theverge.com/news/670773/google-labs-stitch-ui-coding-design-tool), the company is encouraging users to “vibe design,” including with new voice capabilities. I’m so tired of vibing.\n\n![Image 4: Hayden Field](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/06/HAYDEN_BLURPLE.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nHayden Field Mar 18\n\nThe Pentagon filed a rebuttal to Anthropic’s lawsuit.\n\nAnthropic filed a lawsuit earlier this month over its “supply chain risk” designation, but the Department of Defense held firm in a new [court filing](https://www.courtlistener.com/docket/72379655/96/anthropic-pbc-v-us-department-of-war/), alleging that the company could ostensibly “attempt to disable its technology or preemptively alter the behavior of its model either before or during ongoing warfighting operations” in the event it felt its red lines were “being crossed.” The filing added that the Pentagon “deemed that an unacceptable risk to national security.”\n\n![Image 5: Stevie Bonifield](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/STEVIE_BONIFIELD_BLURPLE.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nStevie Bonifield Mar 18\n\nMeta’s NYC store is here to stay.\n\nThe Tardis-blue Meta Lab NYC store on Fifth Avenue in Manhattan is no longer a pop-up shop. Meta [announced on Wednesday](https://www.meta.com/blog/meta-lab-new-locations-new-york-city-fifth-avenue-wynn-las-vegas-west-hollywood-new-york-ai-glasses-demos/) that the skateboarding-themed glasses store is now a “permanent flagship location,” where it will continue selling its [AI smart glasses](https://www.theverge.com/tech/779566/meta-ray-ban-display-hands-on-smart-glasses-price-battery-specs) and Meta Quest headsets.\n\n[![Image 6: The interior of Meta’s NYC flagship store](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/meta-lab-nyc-interior.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&w=2400)](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/meta-lab-nyc-interior.jpg?quality=90&strip=all)\n\n[![Image 7: The exterior of Meta’s NYC flagship store](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/meta-lab-nyc-storefront.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&w=2400)](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/meta-lab-nyc-storefront.jpg?quality=90&strip=all)\n\n**1/2**Image: Meta\n\n![Image 8: DLSS 5: Has Nvidia’s AI graphics technology gone too far?](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/screencapture-nvidia-en-us-geforce-news-dlss5-breakthrough-in-visual-fidelity-for-games-nvidia-dlss-5-resident-evil-requiem-geforce-rtx-comparison-screenshot-001-2026-03-17-20_21_56.png?quality=90&strip=all&crop=21.875%2C0%2C56.25%2C100&w=2400)![Image 9: DLSS 5: Has Nvidia’s AI graphics technology gone too far?](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/screencapture-nvidia-en-us-geforce-news-dlss5-breakthrough-in-visual-fidelity-for-games-nvidia-dlss-5-resident-evil-requiem-geforce-rtx-comparison-screenshot-001-2026-03-17-20_21_56.png?quality=90&strip=all&crop=7.8125%2C0%2C84.375%2C100&w=2400)\n\nRichard Lawler Mar 18\n\n![Image 10: Jess Weatherbed](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/author_profile_images/195820/JESSICA_WEATHERBED.0.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nJess Weatherbed Mar 18\n\nSony working to fight Ghibli-infringing slop.\n\nAlongside building tools to identify [AI song sources](https://www.theverge.com/ai-artificial-intelligence/879865/sony-develops-tech-to-identify-source-material-for-ai-songs), Sony’s R&D division is reportedly training its own “Protective AI” model on content from Studio Ghibli films, which are [popular fodder](https://www.theverge.com/openai/636529/images-chatgpt-openai-studio-ghibli-copyright) for [generated imitation](https://www.theverge.com/tech/638603/studio-ghibli-chatgpt-ai-filter-white-house-meme). Sony hasn’t decided what it’ll do with the model (yet), but it’s designed to eventually stop AI from ripping off _any_ protected content.\n\n![Image 11: Jess Weatherbed](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/author_profile_images/195820/JESSICA_WEATHERBED.0.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nJess Weatherbed Mar 18\n\nWhich anti-AI banner should human creators rally around?\n\n_[BBC News](https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/articles/cj0d6el50ppo)_ has counted eight different initiatives trying to establish a label that distinguishes human-made products and services from those using AI. Experts say a single standard must be chosen to avoid confusing consumers, but getting everyone to agree on what counts as “human-made” is hard because AI is already integrated into so many tools.\n\n[![Image 12: Labels and stamps have been launched by companies and non-profits from the UK, Australia and the US.](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/72c339a0-1eca-11f1-9120-a910fc22c6ac.png.webp?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=2400)](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/72c339a0-1eca-11f1-9120-a910fc22c6ac.png.webp?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0,0,100,100)\n\n![Image 13: Jay Peters](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/01/JAY_BLURPLE.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nJay Peters Mar 17\n\nJensen Huang, on the critical reaction to DLSS 5: “Well, first of all, they’re completely wrong.”\n\n“The reason for that is because, as I have explained very carefully, DLSS 5 fuses controllability of the of geometry and textures and everything about the game with generative AI,” Huang said, [according to _Tom’s Hardware_](https://www.tomshardware.com/pc-components/gpus/jensen-huang-says-gamers-are-completely-wrong-about-dlss-5-nvidia-ceo-responds-to-dlss-5-backlash), and he noted that developers can “fine-tune the generative AI.”\n\n![Image 14: Richard Lawler](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/01/RICHARD_BLURPLE.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nRichard Lawler Mar 17\n\nCiting fake cases in your court filing can be costly.\n\nThey claimed that the court order was “void on its face.” Now [they’re on the hook for $15k each](https://storage.courtlistener.com/recap/gov.uscourts.ca6.152857/gov.uscourts.ca6.152857.50.2.pdf) to start, plus a long list of costs and fees that will certainly add up.\n\n![Image 15: Nvidia’s DLSS 5 is like motion smoothing for video games, but worse](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/Screenshot-2026-03-17-at-1.29.30%E2%80%AFPM.png?quality=90&strip=all&crop=21.825063078217%2C0%2C56.349873843566%2C100&w=2400)![Image 16: Nvidia’s DLSS 5 is like motion smoothing for video games, but worse](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/Screenshot-2026-03-17-at-1.29.30%E2%80%AFPM.png?quality=90&strip=all&crop=7.7375946173255%2C0%2C84.524810765349%2C100&w=2400)\n\n![Image 17: Now everyone in the US is getting Google’s personalized Gemini AI](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/01/google-gemini-ai-personal-intelligence-tire-suggestion-demo.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=22.093023255814%2C0%2C55.813953488372%2C100&w=2400)![Image 18: Now everyone in the US is getting Google’s personalized Gemini AI](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/01/google-gemini-ai-personal-intelligence-tire-suggestion-demo.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=8.1395348837209%2C0%2C83.720930232558%2C100&w=2400)\n\n![Image 19: Microsoft appoints a new Copilot boss after AI leadership shake-up](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/07/STK259_MICROSOFT_COPILOT_2__C.png?quality=90&strip=all&crop=16.666666666667%2C0%2C66.666666666667%2C100&w=2400)![Image 20: Microsoft appoints a new Copilot boss after AI leadership shake-up](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/07/STK259_MICROSOFT_COPILOT_2__C.png?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=2400)\n\n![Image 21: The future of code is exciting and terrifying](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/VRG_VST_0317_Site.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=16.666666666667%2C0%2C66.666666666667%2C100&w=2400)![Image 22: The future of code is exciting and terrifying](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/VRG_VST_0317_Site.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=2400)\n\n![Image 23: Robert Hart](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/09/ROB_H_BLURPLE.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nRobert Hart Mar 17\n\nOpenAI cuts back on “side quests.”\n\nCEO of applications Fidji Simo told staff the company will prioritize coding and enterprise users over the wide array of projects it has been pursuing, the _WSJ_ reports, including [deepfake machine Sora](https://www.theverge.com/ai-artificial-intelligence/893189/openai-chatgpt-sora-integration), [browser Atlas](https://www.theverge.com/ai-artificial-intelligence/803475/openais-ai-powered-browser-chatgpt-atlas-google-chrome-competition-agent), and [gadgets](https://www.theverge.com/ai-artificial-intelligence/882077/openai-chatgpt-smart-speaker-camera-glasses-lamp).\n\n![Image 24: Sean Hollister](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/author_profile_images/196092/sean-nerf-profile-pic..0.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nSean Hollister Mar 16\n\nHere’s the moment Frozen’s Olaf joined the Nvidia GTC 2026 keynote.\n\nNvidia has uploaded the GTC 26 replay, and the embed above _should_ be queued up to the Olaf part. ([I met Olaf yesterday](https://www.theverge.com/tech/895369/olaf-disney-imagineering-frozen-robot-up-close)!) Right after that, you can help me witness what appears to be an entirely AI-generated music video that attempts to summarize the keynote. It is quite the thing.\n\n![Image 25: Stevie Bonifield](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/10/STEVIE_BONIFIELD_BLURPLE.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nStevie Bonifield Mar 16\n\nNvidia is launching NemoClaw, a more secure version of OpenClaw.\n\nDuring [GTC](https://www.theverge.com/ai-artificial-intelligence/895363/how-to-watch-nvidias-gtc-2026-keynote-tap-here) on Monday, Nvidia announced it’s [launching NemoClaw](https://nvidianews.nvidia.com/news/nvidia-announces-nemoclaw), an agentic AI platform that adds privacy and security protections to the autonomous AI platform [OpenClaw](https://www.theverge.com/news/872091/openclaw-moltbot-clawdbot-ai-agent-news) by running it in an “isolated sandbox” environment:\n\n> NemoClaw uses Nvidia Agent Toolkit software to optimize OpenClaw in a single command. It installs OpenShell to provide open models and an isolated sandbox that adds data privacy and security to autonomous agents. This provides the missing infrastructure layer beneath claws to give them the access they need to be productive, while enforcing policy-based security, network and privacy guardrails.\n\n![Image 26: Sean Hollister](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/author_profile_images/196092/sean-nerf-profile-pic..0.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nSean Hollister Mar 16\n\nNvidia is the latest to promise AI data centers in space.\n\n> We’re working with our partners on a new computer called Vera Ruben Space 1, and it’s going to go out to space and start data centers out in space. Now, of course in space there’s no conduction, there’s no convection, there’s just radiation, and so we have to figure out how to cool these systems out in space. But we’ve got lots of great engineers working on it.\n\n![Image 27: DLSS 5 looks like a real-time generative AI filter for video games](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/grokashcroft.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=16.650485436893%2C0%2C66.699029126214%2C100&w=2400)![Image 28: DLSS 5 looks like a real-time generative AI filter for video games](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/grokashcroft.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0.024260067928189%2C100%2C99.951479864144&w=2400)\n\n![Image 29: Teens sue Elon Musk’s xAI over Grok’s AI-generated CSAM](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/05/STK262_GROK_B_C.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=16.666666666667%2C0%2C66.666666666667%2C100&w=2400)![Image 30: Teens sue Elon Musk’s xAI over Grok’s AI-generated CSAM](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/05/STK262_GROK_B_C.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=2400)\n\n![Image 31: Benjamin Netanyahu is struggling to prove he’s not an AI clone](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/Benjamin-Netanyahu-alleged-ai-deepfake-hed.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=16.666666666667%2C0%2C66.666666666667%2C100&w=2400)![Image 32: Benjamin Netanyahu is struggling to prove he’s not an AI clone](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/Benjamin-Netanyahu-alleged-ai-deepfake-hed.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=2400)\n\n![Image 33: Encyclopedia Britannica is suing OpenAI for allegedly ‘memorizing’ its content with ChatGPT](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/gettyimages-141320386.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=16.65%2C0%2C66.7%2C100&w=2400)![Image 34: Encyclopedia Britannica is suing OpenAI for allegedly ‘memorizing’ its content with ChatGPT](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/gettyimages-141320386.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0.02498750624688%2C100%2C99.950024987506&w=2400)\n\n![Image 35: Sean Hollister](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/author_profile_images/196092/sean-nerf-profile-pic..0.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nSean Hollister Mar 16\n\nHow to watch Nvidia’s GTC 2026 keynote: tap here.\n\nThe world’s [first $5 trillion company](https://www.theverge.com/news/809017/nvidia-5-trillion-market-cap-ai) (currently 4.47 trillion) is strutting its stuff in San Jose, California. We’re expecting an AI and robot show... but fingers crossed [for N1 consumer laptop chips](https://www.theverge.com/games/867056/leak-nvidia-n1-n1x-laptops-lenovo-dell) too! Jensen’s keynote starts 11am PT / 2pm ET.\n\n![Image 36: Yahoo CEO Jim Lanzone on reviving the web’s homepage](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/DCD-20260316-Lanzone.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=2400)\n\nHow Yahoo escaped its Verizon death spiral and became profitable again.\n\n![Image 37: Emma Roth](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/author_profile_images/195810/EMMA_ROTH.0.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nEmma Roth Mar 16\n\nMoltbook updates its rules about what you and your AI can do.\n\nJust days after Meta acquired the “social” network for AI agents, the platform has [updated its terms of service](https://www.moltbook.com/terms), stating that users must be 13 years of age or older to use the site and are “solely responsible” for actions taken by their AI agents, whether they “act autonomously or otherwise, and irrespective of whether such actions or omissions were intended.”\n\n![Image 38: This is not a fly uploaded to a computer](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/Screenshot-2026-03-13-at-17.18.37.png?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0.67971723762915%2C100%2C98.640565524742&w=2400)\n\nA lot of buzz, but not much evidence.\n\n![Image 39: OpenAI’s adult mode will reportedly be smutty, not pornographic](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25313355/STK464_PORN_ADULT_CONTENT_2A.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=17.303921568627%2C0%2C65.392156862745%2C100&w=2400)![Image 40: OpenAI’s adult mode will reportedly be smutty, not pornographic](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25313355/STK464_PORN_ADULT_CONTENT_2A.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0.95588235294118%2C0%2C98.088235294118%2C100&w=2400)\n\n![Image 41: Thomas Ricker](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/author_profile_images/196111/IMG_5981_2.0.jpeg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nThomas Ricker Mar 16\n\n“AI can be very dangerous, we have to be very careful with it,” says Trump.\n\n![Image 42: AI companies want to harvest improv actors’ skills to train AI on human emotion](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2026/03/268402_AI_companies_want_to_harvest_improv_actors_skills_to_train_large_AI_models_on_human_emotion_and_tone_CVirginia.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=2400)\n\nThe job requires the ‘ability to recognize, express, and shift between emotions in a way that feels authentic and human.’\n\n![Image 43: Terrence O'Brien](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/02/Terrence-OBrien-headshot-1.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nTerrence O'Brien Mar 14\n\nPalantir’s Maven Smart System is an AI-powered Kanban board for killing people.\n\nThe company recently hosted a series of speakers at [AIPCon](https://www.palantir.com/aipcon/), including Cameron Stanley, the Department of War’s Chief Digital and Artificial Intelligence Officer, who gave a [chilling demo](https://www.threads.com/@bilawal.ai/post/DV1Ev2miINv?xmt=AQF0ZXsOrxjnVEg_QRI1G9MROQaA9NpfBGwJTngl8DSYGsedlthnfzmOCT56rzDgkNtOYNqc&slof=1) of [Palantir’s](https://www.theverge.com/business/872928/palantirs-government-growth)[Maven Smart System](https://blog.palantir.com/maven-smart-system-innovating-for-the-alliance-5ebc31709eea), where anyone or anything can be targeted for a [military strike](https://www.theverge.com/ai-artificial-intelligence/885963/anthropic-dod-pentagon-tech-workers-ai-labs-react) with a “Left click, right click, left click.”\n\n![Image 44: Terrence O'Brien](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/02/Terrence-OBrien-headshot-1.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nTerrence O'Brien Mar 14\n\nAI has nearly killed Buzzfeed, but its CEO has learned nothing.\n\nThree years ago _Buzzfeed_ embraced AI, using it to generate articles and quiz responses. Turns out, nobody wants that. The company posted a [loss of $57.3 million](https://futurism.com/artificial-intelligence/buzzfeed-disastrous-earnings-ai) in 2025 and its stock dropped to just $0.70. But CEO Jonah Peretti is still planning to bring “[new AI apps](https://investors.buzzfeed.com/news-releases/news-release-details/buzzfeed-inc-reports-q4-and-full-year-2025-results)” to market. 🤦\n\n![Image 45: Microsoft’s Copilot AI assistant is coming to current-gen Xbox consoles this year](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25676324/twarren_xboxseriesxwhite__6_.JPG?quality=90&strip=all&crop=16.890243902439%2C0%2C66.219512195122%2C100&w=2400)![Image 46: Microsoft’s Copilot AI assistant is coming to current-gen Xbox consoles this year](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/chorus/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25676324/twarren_xboxseriesxwhite__6_.JPG?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0.33536585365853%2C0%2C99.329268292683%2C100&w=2400)\n\n![Image 47: Dominic Preston](https://platform.theverge.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2025/01/DOM_BLURPLE-1.jpg?quality=90&strip=all&crop=0%2C0%2C100%2C100&w=96)\n\nDominic Preston Mar 13\n\nAlexa, watch your language.\n\nAmazon has expanded its [Alexa Plus personality styles](https://www.theverge.com/tech/884269/amazon-alexa-plus-personality-styles-availability) with a new [“Sassy” option](https://www.theverge.com/tech/894135/amazons-sassy-personality-style-for-alexa-plus-has-a-lot-of-warning-labels#comments). The chili pepper icon hints at this Alexa’s “unfiltered personality,” but don’t worry, Amazon is keeping the spice mild, with only “occasional censored profanity.”\n\n**Chris K.:**","cwd":"/home/gem/workspace/agent/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773882969488}}
